commit.message:
v1.913

        - as ever, you should probably use Email::Address::XS instead
        - this version now requires Perl v5.12
        - some small tweaks to the code to take advantage of v5.12 made
        - update distribution metadata
tests: use done_testing rather than numeric plan
update tests to use v5.12 and warnings
update Changelog for next release
GitHub Actions: add workflow
enjoy the v5.12 life
update author email, perl-window, mailmap

v1.912

        - include the doc updates from 1.911 changelog, oops!
prep next release: oops
Remove deprecation warnings following vulnerability fixes

v1.911

        - just like 1.910, but with doc updates and undeprecation by Jim Brandt

v1.910

        - update parsing to mitigate pathological cases (thanks, sunnavy!)
update changelog
add tests for the order of the extracted emails

short-circuit $name_addr regex if the string can't match $angle_addr

This is to fix the performance issue on some evil strings.

tweak performance by using 2 smaller regex

We can extract addresses with names(like "foo <foo@example.com>") first,
and then bare addresses like "foo@example.com". Doing so not just
simplifies matching rules, but also helps regex engine analyze and
optimize, which could improve performance a lot when encountering evil
strings.

It's implemented to reserve the order of the parsed email addresses,
just like a single regex does.
add tests for cases reported in CVE-2015-7686 and CVE-2018-12558

avoid unnecessary backtrackings

Backtracking could cause serious exponential performance issues, luckily
that we can avoid it here as BNF of email address is not ambiguous.

This fixes CVE-2015-7686 under various $COMMENT_NEST_LEVEL and also
CVE-2018-12558

v1.909

        - add some docs saying "don't use this, it can be busted"
prep next release
pare down some of the deprecation provided

Deprecate Email::Address

Add information about CVE-2015-7686 and Email::Adress::XS into documentation.

Fixes #17

v1.908

        - default to 1 level of nested comments to avoid pathological behaviors
default to one-level of comments

v1.907

        - restore 5.8.x compatibility
work on antique perls again

v1.906

        - the test suite tests parses more directly, which eliminates a number
          of misleading (and possibly wrong) test cases
        - escaped characters in a quoted string are now properly unescaped
          for the ->phrase method, which means things should round trip better
          from their decomposed form
update changelog for new release
improve the "quoted phrase" test a bit

unescape quoted phrase parts

The phrase of: "Bob \"Robert\" Smith" <bob@example.com>

should be q{Bob "Robert" Smith"} and not, as we got,
q{Bob \"Robert\" Smith}, which caused things not to round trip
properly.

It is possible that this changes how bogus input is parsed, and we
should add tests for that.  It improves parsing of valid input,
though.
